---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { data, formatNumber } from "../../lib/site-data";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Method | FrontierGraph"
  description="How FrontierGraph builds a public economics concept graph and ranks candidate research questions."
>
  <main>
    <section class="page-hero">
      <span class="eyebrow">Method</span>
      <h1>The method notes behind the public FrontierGraph release.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        FrontierGraph extracts paper-local graph structure from economics paper text, matches recurring labels into a native concept vocabulary, ranks missing links with deterministic graph rules, and then edits the released list to remove obvious duplicates and repetitive phrasing.
      </p>
      <div class="button-row">
        <span class="field-pill">One canonical public release</span>
        <a class="button-secondary" href="/how-it-works/">How it works</a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={data.downloads.artifacts.working_paper_pdf}>Read paper</a>
        <a class="button-tertiary" href="/downloads/">Downloads</a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href="/graph/">Open literature map</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <article class="content-panel summary-panel">
        <span class="eyebrow">Short version</span>
        <h2>FrontierGraph turns a large published-journal corpus into a reusable concept graph, then ranks the questions that still look structurally under-connected.</h2>
        <p class="card-copy">
          The public release screens <strong>{formatNumber(data.metrics.papers)}</strong> published-journal papers, finds extracted graph structure in
          <strong> {formatNumber(data.metrics.papers_with_extracted_edges)}</strong> of them, and carries
          <strong> {formatNumber(data.metrics.normalized_graph_papers)}</strong> papers into the normalized concept graph used by the benchmark and the site.
        </p>
        <div class="pill-row">
          <span class="field-pill">{formatNumber(data.metrics.native_concepts)} native concepts</span>
          <span class="field-pill">{formatNumber(data.metrics.normalized_links)} normalized links</span>
          <span class="field-pill">{formatNumber(data.metrics.visible_public_questions)} released questions</span>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="section method-stack">
      <details class="method-detail" open>
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Corpus</span>
            <strong>What enters the graph</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The public release starts from an OpenAlex-linked published-journal corpus built from the <strong>FWCI core150 + adjacent150</strong> journal cut. That keeps the site tied to a defined, versioned paper sample rather than to an unconstrained scrape.
          </p>
          <p>
            Each paper contributes a paper-local graph built from title and abstract text. The larger literature object is assembled from those paper-level graphs, not from one global semantic pass over the corpus.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Extraction</span>
            <strong>What the model does, and where it stops</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The model extracts paper-local nodes and edges only. Nodes keep study-local wording where possible, while edges retain directionality, relation type, claim status, and evidence-method metadata when that information is visible in the text.
          </p>
          <p>
            The model stops there. Concept matching, ranking, and release filtering all happen in deterministic downstream layers once the paper-local graph tables are fixed.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Concept identity</span>
            <strong>How local labels become reusable concepts</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            Recurring paper-local labels are matched into a native concept vocabulary rather than left as raw strings. The pipeline starts with lexical normalization and support-gated head concepts, then uses text embeddings to match harder labels to the nearest established concept while keeping mapping provenance.
          </p>
          <p>
            In plain terms, close labels such as spelling variants, local abbreviations, and slightly different phrasings can still land on the same shared concept when the textual similarity is strong enough. The working paper documents the fuller normalization protocol and its release choices in more detail.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Ranking and release</span>
            <strong>How missing links become public research questions</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The ranker combines deterministic graph signals such as path support, local gap structure, motif reinforcement, mediator structure, co-occurrence scarcity, and hub penalties.
          </p>
          <p>
            After ranking, the release filter removes near-synonym loops and repetitive phrasing from the public list, leaving <strong>{formatNumber(data.metrics.visible_public_questions)}</strong> questions in the released browsing surface.
          </p>
          <p>
            Curated cards use editorial question wording when they present a research direction, while the broader machine-ranked lists keep neutral pair wording so the public surface does not imply causal direction from storage order alone.
          </p>
          <div class="button-row">
            <a class="button-secondary" href="/questions/">See Research Questions</a>
            <a class="button-tertiary" href="/how-it-works/">Read How it works</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Glossary</span>
            <strong>What the raw graph terms mean</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body glossary-grid">
          <article>
            <h3>Path support</h3>
            <p>The direct pair is weak or missing, but nearby concepts already connect the two sides of the question.</p>
          </article>
          <article>
            <h3>Gap structure</h3>
            <p>The surrounding neighborhood looks fuller than the direct link itself, so the pair may be lagging behind nearby work.</p>
          </article>
          <article>
            <h3>Motif reinforcement</h3>
            <p>Repeated local graph patterns that reinforce the same connection. Useful for ranking, but hidden on the main public cards.</p>
          </article>
          <article>
            <h3>Mediator count</h3>
            <p>The number of nearby concepts that help connect the two sides of the pair through the observed graph.</p>
          </article>
          <article>
            <h3>Release filter</h3>
            <p>The release filter removes near-synonym loops and repeated wording so the public list stays easier to browse.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
